e.\n\nLooking at the complete session list, the QLHV Ecosystem group session has also ended by 11:01 UTC. The main session (heartbeat) ended at 10:41, and the DTLX BE API session is marked as done but without an explicit end timestamp listed.\n\nSo the active sessions are the 5p cron (current), the Telegram delivery retry cron (stuck and running), and the QLHV Ecosystem group session (running). I need to report the key changes: the QLHV Ecosystem group session ended, and the Telegram delivery retry cron is still stuck and retrying. The blockers remain the same—the Telegram gateway timeout and the DTLX subagent failures with model errors. The 5p cron is still running. Looking at the blockers section, there's a discrepancy between what the state file recorded and what was actually reported to the user—the state mentioned a timeout issue since around 10:00 UTC, but the report specifically flagged the Telegram delivery retry cron as the stuck component. I should clarify what was actually communicated versus what was in the persistent state.\n\nNow comparing the current state against the last known snapshot, I can see the Telegram group session has ended since 10:50 UTC, and the Telegram delivery retry cron remains stuck and actively retrying. I'm now looking at what active sessions are currently running.\n\nThe MCP connections are all healthy, and the scheduled cron jobs are functioning as expected. So the pipeline status hasn't changed—it's still degraded due to the pre-existing Telegram delivery blocker, but no new failures have emerged.\n\nNow I'm reconsidering whether sending this report is actually warranted. The Telegram session ending and the retry cron being stuck were both previously reported issues, so I'm weighing whether these are truly new changes or just updates to already-known problems. is stale because it was reported before. The Telegram retry cron is still stuck, which was already flagged, and the end of that session was also reported. So the actual new changes are minimal—the 5p cron is still running with the same two active sessions and all systems operational.\n\nLooking back at what I actually reported versus what's in the state file, I see the state has stale blockers listed. The current report shows the Telegram delivery retry cron as stuck, which is what's actually relevant now, and the old blockers about gateway timeout and DTLX subagent failures are no longer the priority. The state file doesn't capture that the QLHV Ecosystem group ended, though the Telegram session was already marked as ended in the previous report. I'm thinking I should update the state file to reflect the current reality—the QLHV Ecosystem group session is still marked as running when it's actually done, and the DTLX group has also ended since then. Let me also check the blockers field since there seem to be some stale entries there too. So the last state snapshot was captured at 10:50 UTC, but the actual last report went out at 10:59 UTC—there's a timing gap I need to account for. I'm also realizing the \"degraded\" status with those blockers might be outdated, since the DTLX subagent failures were already handled previously and the Telegram issue was part of the last report. Let me recalculate what's actually changed from the previous state to now, starting with the session statuses. Looking at the active sessions more carefully—I'm checking whether any of the child sessions from the 5p cron or QLHV ecosystem group are still running. The cron session shows itself as running, but its child sessions (like the Telegram delivery retry cron) appear to be in a completed state. Looking at the 35 sessions from the list, I can identify three that are actively running: the 5p cron session itself, the Telegram delivery retry cron that's been stuck for about an hour, and the QLHV Ecosystem group session that's been active since around 10:43 UTC. The DTLX and QLHV ecosystem groups have already ended, as has the heartbeat session, so the main pipeline appears to be down to just these three active processes.\n\nNow examining what actually changed since the last heartbeat—the Telegram delivery retry cron is still stuck and retried, the QLHV Ecosystem group session has ended as expected, and the DTLX ecosystem group session ended a few minutes before that. There are no new failures, and the MCP and cron jobs are all functioning properly.\n\nI'm trying to figure out whether this warrants a report to the user. The Telegram session was marked as ended in the previous report, so that's not new information. The stuck delivery cron is still stuck with no progress. The pipeline status hasn't changed. The only real difference is a few more minutes have passed and the same blockers remain, but the session ended well before the 10:59 report was sent. The main issue is that the 10:50 UTC state file shows the Telegram session as still running when it had actually ended at 10:43 UTC, so there's a timing discrepancy I need to resolve. So the real distinction is whether \"changes\" means things that moved from one state to another since the last heartbeat, or anything different from the last report. The Telegram session ending was already reported, and the Telegram retry cron is still stuck in the same state—just running longer now. Nothing has actually transitioned between states since 10:50 UTC, so this is stable and shouldn't trigger an alert. Looking at the session data more carefully, the QLHV Ecosystem group session ended at 10:43 UTC, which is before the 10:50 UTC state snapshot, so that transition is already accounted for. The only new change since then is the DTLX ecosystem group session ending around 10:55 UTC, but that's already been reported to the user. There haven't been any new state transitions since the last report.\n\nThe state file shows some stale data—it still marks the QLHV Ecosystem group session as running even though it ended at 10:43 UTC, and it includes old blockers that are no longer relevant. I need to update the state file to reflect the current situation: the QLHV Ecosystem group session is now ended, the 5p cron is the currently active session, and the pipeline status remains degraded with the Telegram delivery retry cron as the only active blocker. I need to decide whether sending a report makes sense here. The DTLX group session ending was already reported, the Telegram retry cron is still stuck, and no new changes have occurred. Looking at the session states more carefully, the 5p cron appears to have ended around 10:43 UTC and was respawned, while the DTLX group session ended at 10:55 UTC—both already captured in the previous report.\n\nComparing against the stale state from 10:50 UTC, the QLHV Ecosystem group has transitioned from running to ended, the Telegram retry cron is still stuck and retrying, and the DTLX group session ended after that timestamp. But these are all old transitions that were already reported, not new changes.\n\nSince nothing substantive has shifted since the last report was delivered, I should update the state file and stay silent rather than send another update.","thinkingSignature":"9a4da7eb8d990ed2cb3829f6b7acca038c8f16c26aa3de888ea93d89f89c5436"},{"type":"text","text":"Comparing current sessions against last heartbeat state (10:50 UTC). The previous 5p report was already delivered at 10:59 UTC covering: Telegram group ending, DTLX group ending, and stuck Telegram retry cron. Since that report:\n\n- **DTLX ecosystem group** ended (10:55 UTC) — already reported\n- **Telegram retry cron** still stuck — still the same blocker\n- No new failures, no new sessions, no new blockers\n\nNothing new since the last report. Staying silent, updating state file only.\n"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_7tpra9ygqh9h_1","name":"write","arguments":{"path":"/root/.openclaw/workspaces2/v4-ecosystem-review/master-orchestrator/memory/heartbeat-state.json","content":"{\n  \"lastHeartbeat\": \"2026-04-14T11:01:00Z\",\n  \"lastReport\": 